5. Lemma Three: Discrete Covariant Derivative and Geometric Autogenesis of Superconducting Gauge Fields

5.1 Construction of a Discrete Gauge Field

Definition 5.1 (Combinatorial Covariant Derivative): Let the discrete phase field of shared links be Θ(r_i), defined on lattice nodes i. Let A_ij be the orientation tensor contribution of background shared links between nodes i and j. Define the combinatorial covariant derivative:

D_ij Θ ≡ Θ(r_j) − Θ(r_i) − A_ij

where:

Θ(r_i) ∈ Z is the phase of the shared link at node i (count of reconnection steps)
A_ij is the background orientation field generated between nodes i, j due to periodic arrangement of atomic nuclei, defined as the minimum number of reconnection steps along the i→j direction
All quantities are purely discrete, independent of any continuous spatial metric.

5.2 Geometric Definition of the Superconducting State

Definition 5.2 (Superconducting State): If and only if for all nearest-neighbor node pairs ⟨i, j⟩, the covariant derivative vanishes:

D_ij Θ = 0, ∀⟨i,j⟩ ∈ conducting network

the system is in global phase locking—all shared links perform helical motion in perfect synchrony.

5.3 Discrete Derivation of the First London Equation

Derivation 5.1 (First London Equation):

The macroscopic current density J is defined in TDMU as the directed shared link flux. When the system deviates from the perfect superconducting state but still maintains phase coherence, there exists a residual value of the covariant derivative. This residual drives the directed link flux:

J ∝ Σ_⟨i,j⟩ D_ij Θ

In the continuum limit, D_ij Θ corresponds to the covariant derivative ∇Θ − A, hence:

J = −(1/Λ) A

where Λ is the geometric inertia constant of the shared link network, determined by the total number of links per unit volume N_total: Λ ∝ 1/N_total.

This is the purely discrete form of the first London equation. ■

5.4 Geometric Necessity of the Meissner Effect

Derivation 5.2 (Meissner Effect):

Taking the discrete curl (summing along the smallest closed path) of the London equation:

∇ × J = −(1/Λ) (∇ × A) = −(1/Λ) B

Inside the superconducting state, by Definition 5.2, all D_ij Θ = 0, so the spatial distribution of J is completely determined by the configuration of A_ij, and ∇ × J = 0.

From this it follows that B = 0 strictly holds inside the superconductor.

The penetration depth λ_L = √Λ is defined as the geometric yielding step count of the shared link network—i.e., the characteristic length over which an external orientation gradient (magnetic field), upon entering the synchronized link network, is completely screened after λ_L steps of reconnection propagation. ■

5.5 Topological Necessity of Flux Quantization

Derivation 5.3 (Flux Quantization):

Consider a closed path C on a superconducting ring. The phase Θ must return to the same discrete count after one full loop, so the total phase change is an integer multiple of 2π (Θ is the number of helical steps modulo 2π; 2π corresponds to the equivalence of the phase returning to the initial count value after completing one full cycle on the discrete helical path).

Summing the covariant derivative along the closed path:

∮_C DΘ · dl = 2π n, n ∈ Z

In the superconducting state, DΘ = 0 holds inside the ring body, but along a closed path enclosing the hole, the contribution of A is not canceled. Thus:

∮_C DΘ · dl = ∮_C A · dl = Φ

Combining:

Φ = n · Φ₀, Φ₀ = 2π

Magnetic flux is rigorously quantized in TDMU geometric natural units as integer multiples of the fundamental unit Φ₀ = 2π.

